<p>The Economics department offers a Bachelor degree of Arts and a Bachelor degree of Science. A minor in Economics and a minor in Economics Education. In addition to the core classes, BYU-Idaho students studying Economics will choose an area of concentration and a complimentary minor or two clusters as approved by their advisor. 15-18 credits of upper-division classes represent an area of concentration with some possible choices listed here:</p>
<ol>
<li>Job Ready</li>
<li>Graduate Study</li>
<li>Pre-MBA</li>
<li>Pre-Law</li>
<li>International</li>
<li>Agriculture</li>
</ol>
<p>A description of each of these areas of concentration can be found in the <a href="http://www.byui.edu/Documents/catalog/2013-2014/Economics%280%29.pdf" title="Catalog" target="_parent">BYU-Idaho Catalog</a>.<br /><br /></p>
